[
    {
        "content": "<p>here's a question that I feel I should already know the answer to, but don't: Kan complexes are the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-analogue of groupoids; quasi-categories are the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-analogue of categories; simplicial sets are the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-analgoue of... what? just sets?</p>",
        "id": 366209020,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686753951
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>maybe somewhat more concretely, in the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-setting we have fully faithful functors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><mo>↪</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo>↪</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Kan}\\hookrightarrow\\mathsf{Quasicat}\\hookrightarrow\\mathsf{sSet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7054em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Kan</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8194em;vertical-align:-0.125em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Quasicat</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">sSet</span></span></span></span></span>, and these inclusions have some adjoints — which category should appear in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">d</mi></mrow><mo>↪</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo>↪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">?</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Grpd}\\hookrightarrow\\mathsf{Cat}\\hookrightarrow\\mathsf{?}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Grpd</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7054em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Cat</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">?</span></span></span></span> so that analogous adjoints exist (if possible)</p>",
        "id": 366209723,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686754069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably the closest analogue would be 2-truncated simplicial sets: presheaves on the full subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span></span></span></span> containing only [0], [1], [2].</p>",
        "id": 366211009,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686754285
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>do these things turn up in many places? the thing that surprised me the most when I thought about this question was that, despite how great Kan complexes and quasi-categories are, simplicial sets themselves are still very interesting to study and there's a great deal of research concerning them — groupoids and categories are both very well studied, but I can't think of anywhere where I've read about 2-truncated simplicial sets before</p>",
        "id": 366212573,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686754565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The first application of simplicial sets I can think of that isn't just an application of Kan complexes or quasi-categories involves using them to index diagrams to take limits and colimits of, e.g. \"bar constructions\".  An analogue of this does appear in category theory under the name (co) <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/descent%20object\">[[descent object]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 366215525,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686755107
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And, of course, the 1-truncated version is just reflexive graphs and (co)equalizers, and those appear all over the place.</p>",
        "id": 366215727,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686755152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Did you have other examples in mind?</p>",
        "id": 366215795,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686755163
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh that's a nice point of view I hadn't thought about</p>",
        "id": 366234243,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686758606
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for me, simplicial sets are things that you do homotopy theory with, and the homotopy theory of simplicial presheaves is everywhere in the sort of work that i do</p>",
        "id": 366234459,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686758631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think I could say that 1-truncated simplicial sets naturally arise in this setting (in that you can just look at the 1-truncation of the Čech nerve for most classical purposes), but not 2-truncated</p>",
        "id": 366234803,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686758680
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I suppose the other thing is the two model structures on simplicial sets that give you quasi-categories or Kan complexes as your fibrant objects, but I don't know if (1-)groupoids and (1-) categories arise in some similar way from a construction on 2-truncated simplicial sets</p>",
        "id": 366235119,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686758744
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When you say \"simplicial sets are things that you do homotopy theory with\", you're really treating simplicial sets as presentations of Kan complexes.  So in that sense, the analogue in 1-category theory would just be working with groupoids.</p>",
        "id": 366239471,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686759656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>1-category theory is pleasant enough that in most cases we don't need a notion of \"presentation\" for our 1-groupoids and can work with them directly, so for the most part you don't see an analogue of simplicial sets containing Kan complexes there.</p>",
        "id": 366239660,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686759706
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ok, I think you've sort of drilled down to what my real question should have been, which is \"if simplicial sets are a context in which we can describe <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-groupoids/-categories, then what is the analogous context for 1-groupoids/-categories?\"</p>",
        "id": 366242441,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686760316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in which case your answer of 2-truncated simplicial sets makes sense, because when we talk about categories and groupoids we talk about objects, morphisms, and commutativity of diagrams</p>",
        "id": 366242625,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686760354
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>at least, that's how i'm understanding your answer!</p>",
        "id": 366242665,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686760364
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280178\">Tim Hosgood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Kan.20is.20to.20groupoid.20as.20sSet.20is.20to.2E.2E.2E.20what.3F/near/366235119\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I suppose the other thing is the two model structures on simplicial sets that give you quasi-categories or Kan complexes as your fibrant objects, but I don't know if (1-)groupoids and (1-) categories arise in some similar way from a construction on 2-truncated simplicial sets</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>is this something that still holds true in the 1-dimensional world?</p>",
        "id": 366242884,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1686760421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably.  You might have to use 3-truncated simplicial sets to get associativity.  I don't remember if anyone has written down the details.</p>",
        "id": 366253339,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686762872
    }
]